ginal Australian social life. Today's Aboriginal media include genres of country music and hip-hop; radio requests and broadcast speech; visual graphs of a digital audio timeline; as well as the statistical media of audience research and the discursive and numerical figures of state audits and cultural policy formation. In each of these diverse instances the mediatized voice has become a site for overlapping and at times discordant forms of political, expressive, and institutional creativity.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAboriginal Australians in mass media. 0aCommunication and culturezAustralia, Northern. 0aCommunication in anthropologyzAustralia, Northern. 0aPolitics and culturezAustralia, Northern. 0aRadioxProduction and directionzAustralia, Northern. 0aSoundxRecording and reproducingzAustralia, Northern. 4aAboriginal Australia, media, radio, voice, sound studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822374428zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822374428423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822374428.jpg  a978-3-11-070808-0  DUK Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles